pistomp-recovery (0.1.0-23) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Crash screen now reports "crashed" instead of the misleading
    "activating" ActiveState when a service has crashed and Restart=always
    has already queued the next attempt. The label is driven by systemd's
    Result property (exit-code, signal, core-dump, ...) which persists
    across ActiveState transitions and only resets on a successful start,
    so the root-cause service is identifiable even mid-restart-loop.
  * Pin the "<--" crash marker to the first failed service in the chain
    (the actual root cause) rather than only firing on ActiveState=failed,
    which almost never shows up in practice due to the OnFailure race.
  * Capture per-service Result in CrashInfo.service_results so the screen
    can distinguish "crashed and restarting" from "clean inactive wait".
  * Fetch 100 journal lines for the on-screen log textarea (was 10) so the
    last-6 slice catches the actual traceback even when a restart loop has
    filled the journal with systemd's own Starting/Started lines above it.
    The deeper fullscreen log viewer already fetched 100; both now match.

 -- Cam Gorrie <sastraxi@gmail.com>  Sun, 05 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000

pistomp-recovery (0.1.0-22) trixie; urgency=medium

  * Refuse pi-stomp apt updates when its source tree is git-expanded
    (e.g. via util/expand-git.sh); apt would otherwise overwrite the
    developer's git-managed checkout. The System updates row for pi-stomp
    shows the local short hash (suffixed with '*' if the working tree is
    dirty) instead of the apt version, and the version-upgrade badge is
    rendered in red to flag the blocked upgrade.
  * When pi-stomp is filtered from an "Update All" run, the badge on the
    Update All row reflects the actual install count rather than the total
    update count, and the confirm dialog notes that pi-stomp is being
    skipped because the user is working from git.
  * Add Target.info: when set, the row opens an OK-only info dialog
    (centered OK button, click to dismiss) instead of a No/Yes confirm.
    Used for the "Cannot update pi-stomp" informational case.

